  "output": "I read through the core modules — this is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (fetchers → filters → SQLite dedup store → notifiers), not a React app, so I adapted the categories to what's actually present. Findings below are grounded in the actual code, not speculative.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` loops over every fetched job and does **one SELECT + one INSERT/UPDATE per row**:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nAmazon/Microsoft fetchers alone can return 1,000-4,000 listings per run (`max_pages=40`, 10/page), so this is 2,000-8,000 individual round trips to SQLite every pipeline run.\n\n**Fix:** batch-fetch existing hashes with `key IN (...)` (chunked for SQLite's variable limit), then use `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\",\n            chunk).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    new, changed, inserts, updates, touches = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touches.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ..., :now, :now)\", inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", updates)\n    if touches:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touches)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis cuts round trips from ~2N to `N/500` selects + 3 batch writes.\n\n## 2. React re-renders — N/A\n\nNo frontend in this repo (it's a CLI/async pipeline). Skipping this category rather than inventing findings.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job, `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)`/`_compile(include)` **on every call** — recompiling the same include/exclude regex list from scratch for every single job:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFor a run with thousands of jobs and even a handful of keywords, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls.\n\n**Fix:** compile once outside the loop, pass compiled patterns through:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(rules[\"max_age_days\"]))\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(and change `match()` to iterate the pre-compiled lists directly instead of calling `_compile` internally).\n\n## 4. Redundant computation — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies the discarded `raw` field, `models.py:71-75`\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # recursively deep-copies every field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)     # ...then immediately throws that copy away\n    ...\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively walks and deep-copies nested dicts/lists. For sources that stash the full API payload in `raw` (lever, ashby, smartrecruiters, recruitee, workable — these can carry full job-description blobs), this does real work copying data that's discarded on the very next line. `to_row()` runs for every new/changed job on every run.\n\n**Fix:** build the row dict directly, skipping `raw` instead of copying-then-dropping it:\n\n```python\nfrom dataclasses import fields\n\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = {f.name: getattr(self, f.name) for f in fields(self) if f.name != \"raw\"}\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\n## 5. Caching / indexing opportunity\n\n`added_since()` (`store.py:111-119`) filters and sorts on `first_seen` with no index on that column (only `key` PK and `idx_jobs_company` exist). As `jobs.db` grows, this becomes a full table scan on every `agent.py db-new` call. Add:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n## 6. Memory leaks — none found\n\nChecked the two resource-holding paths and both are handled correctly:\n- `Store` connections are always opened via `with Store(...) as store:` (pipeline.py:42, agent.py:73/126) — closed on exit.\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` is closed in a `finally` block when it owns the client (fetchers.py:783-787).\n\nNo unbounded caches, no growing global state.\n\n## Minor note (not urgent)\n\n`notify.py`'s `dispatch()` runs `httpx.post`/`smtplib` synchronously at the tail of an `async def run()` (pipeline.py:44) — blocks the event loop briefly. Harmless today since nothing else awaits concurrently at that point, but if notifiers grow (more webhooks, retries), moving `dispatch` to a thread via `asyncio.to_thread` would avoid stalling the loop.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** #1 (N+1 diff) and #3 (regex recompilation) are the real wins — both scale with job count and this pipeline is explicitly designed to pull thousands of listings from Amazon/Microsoft. #4 and #5 are smaller but free. Want me to implement any of these?\n",
